Containers should run a single primary long-lived process which defines the container’s lifecycle, health, and exit status. The container should terminate when the primary process exits.
Running multiple long-lived processes within the same container is discouraged, as it complicates health monitoring, logging, scaling, and failure recovery. For example, if a container runs both Java and Python processes, the container may continue running even if one of the processes has failed, resulting in hidden application degradation.
When multiple cooperating processes are required, each process should run in its own container and be co-located within the same Kubernetes Pod. This allows processes to communicate over localhost or shared volumes while preserving process isolation and independent health management.
Some exception scenarios may exist, particularly with third-party vendor applications that internally spawn worker processes or combine runtimes across multiple languages. These cases should remain the exception rather than the standard approach for internally developed JPMC applications.
Adhering to a single primary process per container improves health reporting, resilience, operational visibility, and independent scaling behavior.
